04"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11990"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44686"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63636"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA woman presents requesting emergency contraception after unprotected sexual intercourse 48 hours ago. Her doctor prescribes her levonorgestrel emergency contraception.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of levonorgestrel emergency contraception?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents or delays ovulation","Destroys fertilised ovum","Prevents implantation of fertilised ovum","Creates hostile cervical mucus","Causes immediate menstrual bleeding"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELevonorgestrel emergency contraception primarily works by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing or delaying ovulation\u003C/strong\u003E. It does this by suppressing the surge of luteinising hormone that triggers ovulation. It does not \u003Cstrong\u003Edestroy fertilised ovum\u003C/strong\u003E. However, if ovulation has already occurred and fertilization happens, it may also \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent implantation of fertilised ovum\u003C/strong\u003E by altering the endometrial lining, though this is not its primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile it may \u003Cstrong\u003Ecreate hostile cervical mucus\u003C/strong\u003E, this is not the primary mechanism of action. The medication does not \u003Cstrong\u003Ecause immediate menstrual bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E, though it may alter the timing of the next menstrual period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELevonorgestrel is most effective when taken within 72 hours of unprotected intercourse, though it can be given up to 120 hours. The copper intrauterine device is the most effective form of emergency contraception when inserted within 5 days of unprotected intercourse. The third emergency contraception option is ulipristal acetate that works by delaying ovulation by inhibiting progesterone receptors and is effective up to 120 hours (5 days) after unprotected intercourse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Emergency contraceptives work primarily by preventing or delaying ovulation","Levonorgestrel emergency contraception is most effective when taken within 72 hours of unprotected intercourse","Copper intrauterine devices are the most effective form of emergency contraception when inserted within 5 days"],"references":["Black KI, Hussainy SY. Emergency contraception: Oral and intrauterine options. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(10):722-726. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29036770/","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49083"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49083"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T20:38:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T20:38:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63636"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"htt